{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17540194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17540194"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:51:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16745"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16745","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16745"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.04,0.02,0.8,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9436"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66735"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9436"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16745"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52188"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"564"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2320"},{"type":"tags","id":"4068"},{"type":"tags","id":"4192"},{"type":"tags","id":"4193"},{"type":"tags","id":"4195"},{"type":"tags","id":"4199"},{"type":"tags","id":"4954"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"10740"},{"type":"tags","id":"10950"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11638"},{"type":"tags","id":"12801"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22302"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43657"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66735","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66735"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 17-year-old woman presents to the gynaecology clinic with her parent because she has not yet had her first menstrual period. She has noticed that most of her friends started their periods several years ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. Her height is 147 cm (below 3rd percentile for age) and weight is 45 kg. Her parent reports that she has always been small for her age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has Tanner stage 3 breast development. There is a low posterior hairline, widely spaced nipples, and cubitus valgus. External genitalia appear normal for age. Investigations reveal follicle stimulating hormone 65 IU/L (1.0-4.5), luteinizing hormone 45 IU/L (1.0-7.0), and oestradiol 40 pmol/L (100-600).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following investigations is most appropriate to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Transvaginal ultrasound","Testosterone level","Pelvic magnetic resonance imaging","Karyotype analysis","17-hydroxyprogesterone level"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features highly suggestive of Turner syndrome, including primary amenorrhea, short stature, and characteristic physical findings such as widely spaced nipples, low posterior hairline, and cubitus valgus. The elevated gonadotropins (FSH and LH) with low oestradiol indicate primary ovarian failure, which is typical in Turner syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EKaryotype analysis\u003C/strong\u003E is the gold standard investigation to confirm Turner syndrome, which is caused by complete or partial absence of one X chromosome (45,XO). This test will definitively establish the diagnosis and guide management decisions regarding hormone replacement therapy and screening for associated conditions.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPelvic magnetic resonance imaging\u003C/strong\u003E may show streak ovaries but is not necessary for diagnosis. While it can provide detailed anatomical information, it cannot confirm the underlying chromosomal abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETestosterone level\u003C/strong\u003E measurement would be more relevant if virilisation was present or if there was concern about disorders of androgen excess, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransvaginal ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate in a 16-year-old who has never been sexually active. While pelvic ultrasound might show streak ovaries, it cannot confirm the diagnosis of Turner syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E17-hydroxyprogesterone level\u003C/strong\u003E is used to diagnose congenital adrenal hyperplasia, which typically presents with virilisation and is not suggested by this patient\u0027s presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnce Turner syndrome is confirmed, the patient will require ongoing multidisciplinary care including hormone replacement therapy, regular screening for associated conditions (cardiac, renal, thyroid), and psychological support. Growth hormone therapy may be considered if diagnosed at a younger age.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Karyotype analysis is the definitive investigation to confirm Turner syndrome in patients with primary amenorrhea.","Turner syndrome should be suspected in females with short stature, primary amenorrhea, and other characteristic physical features.","Elevated follicle stimulating hormone and low oestradiol are typical biochemical findings in Turner syndrome but are not diagnostic."],"references":["Conway GS. Primary Amenorrhoea [Internet]. O\u0026G Magazine. 2017 [cited 2024 Dec 1];19(3). Available from: https://www.ogmagazine.org.au/19/3-19/primary-amenorrhoea/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52188"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16745"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanation